<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/aluminum> skos:definition "Aluminium (in Commonwealth English) or Aluminum (in American English) is a chemical element in the boron group with symbol Al and atomic number 13. It is a silvery-white, soft, nonmagnetic, ductile metal." ;
    skos:exactMatch "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aluminium" ;
    skos:historyNote "Wikipedia" ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Aluminum" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/area> skos:definition "Area of a measurement location" ;
    skos:historyNote "Originally from the CUAHSI HIS VariableNameCV.  See: http://his.cuahsi.org/mastercvreg/edit_cv11.aspx?tbl=VariableNameCV." ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Area" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/arsenic> skos:definition "Arsenic is a chemical element with symbol As and atomic number 33. Arsenic occurs in many minerals, usually in combination with sulfur and metals, but also as a pure elemental crystal. Arsenic is a metalloid. It has various allotropes, but only the gray form, which has a metallic appearance, is important to industry." ;
    skos:exactMatch "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arsenic" ;
    skos:historyNote "Wikipedia" ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:note "Added to support Critical Zone Observatory (CZO) data use cases. " ;
    skos:prefLabel "Arsenic" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/barium> skos:definition "Barium is a chemical element with symbol Ba and atomic number 56. It is the fifth element in group 2 and is a soft, silvery alkaline earth metal. Because of its high chemical reactivity, barium is never found in nature as a free element. Its hydroxide, known in pre-modern times as baryta, does not occur as a mineral, but can be prepared by heating barium carbonate." ;
    skos:exactMatch "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barium" ;
    skos:historyNote "Wikipedia" ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:note "Added to support Critical Zone Observatory (CZO) data use cases. " ;
    skos:prefLabel "Barium" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/cadmium> skos:definition "Cadmium is a chemical element with symbol Cd and atomic number 48. This soft, bluish-white metal is chemically similar to the two other stable metals in group 12, zinc and mercury. Like zinc, it demonstrates oxidation state +2 in most of its compounds, and like mercury, it has a lower melting point than the transition metals in groups 3 through 11. Cadmium and its congeners in group 12 are often not considered transition metals, in that they do not have partly filled d or f electron shells in the elemental or common oxidation states. The average concentration of cadmium in Earth's crust is between 0.1 and 0.5 parts per million (ppm)." ;
    skos:exactMatch "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cadmium" ;
    skos:historyNote "Wikipedia" ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:note "Added to support Critical Zone Observatory (CZO) data use cases. " ;
    skos:prefLabel "Cadmium" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/chloroform> skos:definition "Chloroform (CHCl3), a haloform" ;
    skos:historyNote "Originally from the CUAHSI HIS VariableNameCV.  See: http://his.cuahsi.org/mastercvreg/edit_cv11.aspx?tbl=VariableNameCV." ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Chloroform" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/chromium> skos:definition "Chromium is a chemical element with symbol Cr and atomic number 24. It is the first element in group 6. It is a steely-grey, lustrous, hard and brittle transition metal. Chromium boasts a high usage rate as a metal that is able to be highly polished while resisting tarnishing. Chromium is also the main component of stainless steel, a popular steel alloy due to its uncommonly high specular reflection. Simple polished chromium reflects almost 70% of the visible spectrum, with almost 90% of infrared light waves being reflected. The name of the element is derived from the Greek word χρῶμα, chrōma, meaning color, because many chromium compounds are intensely colored. " ;
    skos:exactMatch "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromium" ;
    skos:historyNote "Wikipedia" ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:note "Added to support Critical Zone Observatory (CZO) data use cases. " ;
    skos:prefLabel "Chromium" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/coliformFecal> skos:definition "Fecal Coliform" ;
    skos:historyNote "Originally from the CUAHSI HIS VariableNameCV.  See: http://his.cuahsi.org/mastercvreg/edit_cv11.aspx?tbl=VariableNameCV." ;
    skos:inScheme <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Coliform, fecal" ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename> .

<http://vocabulary.odm2.org/variablename/coliformTotal> skos:definition "Total Coliform" ;
    skos:historyNote "Originally from the CUAHSI HIS VariableNameCV.  See: http://his.cuahsi.org/mastercvreg/edit_cv11.aspx?tbl=VariableNameCV." ;
