<https://data.usbr.gov/rise/api/parameter-group/8> skos:broader <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_ee622e19> ;
    skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_3e018a2a> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Power Generation"@en .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_b0df653d> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:note "This group includes parameters describing the status, performance, and configuration of monitoring equipment and sensors, such as battery levels, voltage, instrument settings, and related operational metrics. This group does not originally exist in RISE. Some parameters related to equipment in RISE (such as those associated with Acoustic Doppler Velocimeters) are classified under Bedload."@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "Equipment"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_111cb96b> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:note "This group contains RISE parameters classified under parameterGroupId 14: Gage Height. It also includes gage height parameters reported by usgs-sta, snotel-edr, and other sources.  Gage height (or stage) represents the height of the water surface relative to a reference level, known as a datum. When a datum is defined, measurements are referenced to a fixed elevation (e.g., mean sea level or a local benchmark), allowing for consistent comparison across time and locations. In contrast, values reported without a defined datum are relative measurements and may not be directly comparable across sites.  In cases where the datum is not defined, these measurements can be interpreted as water depth. For this reason, such parameters may also be considered within the River Characteristics group."@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "Stream Stage / Gage Height (current/historical)"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_1805cd26> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_3e018a2a> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Data Sources"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_3e018a2a> .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_b0cbf49d> rdfs:seeAlso "https://cwms-data.usace.army.mil/cwms-data/parameters"^^xsd:anyURI,
        "https://water.sec.usace.army.mil/cda/reporting/"^^xsd:anyURI,
        "https://water.sec.usace.army.mil/cda/reporting/providers/projects"^^xsd:anyURI ;
    skos:broader <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_868fb8ce> ;
    skos:editorialNote "Kyle Onda says the API we use at https://water.sec.usace.army.mil/cda/reporting/ is actually a wrapper around the API found here  https://cwms-data.usace.army.mil/cwms-data/swagger-ui.html.  The former uses a subset of the parameters also found and described at https://cwms-data.usace.army.mil/cwms-data/parameters ;  More context on this can be found at https://github.com/USACE/cwms-data-api/discussions/956"@en ;
    skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_3e018a2a> ;
    skos:prefLabel "USACE Access2Water Parameters"@en .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_b940d355> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:note "This group contains the RISE parameters from parameterGroupId 8: Power Generation. It includes variables related to hydropower production and plant operations, such as electricity generation, installed capacity, and energy use, as well as associated hydraulic conditions including flow releases and water surface elevations (e.g., forebay and tailrace). These variables describe how water is stored, routed, and released for power generation."@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "Power Generation"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

