<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_ea9c8330> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Bedload"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_a4fc2f36> skos:definition "This group includes parameters that characterize the hydrological, thermal, and biogeochemical state of the soil, including soil moisture content (e.g., volumetric water content and percent saturation), soil temperature, soil water potential, and soil gas concentrations (e.g., carbon dioxide and oxygen). It may also include variables related to measurement techniques, such as dielectric properties and cosmic-ray neutron counts used to estimate soil moisture. These parameters describe the storage, availability, and movement of water within the soil, as well as the thermal and gas conditions that regulate processes such as infiltration, evapotranspiration, soil respiration, and land–atmosphere interactions."@en ;
    skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Soil"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_e9e56729> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:note "This group includes parameters related to snowpack conditions and snow processes, such as snow depth, snow water equivalent, snow density, temperature within the snowpack, and precipitation in the form of snow. These variables describe the accumulation, physical properties, and melting potential of snow, and are essential for understanding water storage and runoff generation in snow-dominated regions."@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "Snow"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_e41cecd5> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:note " This group contains the RISE parameters from parameterGroupId 10: Lake/Reservoir Outflow"@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "Lake/Reservoir Outflow"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

<https://data.usbr.gov/rise/api/parameter-group/21> skos:broader <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_ee622e19> ;
    skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_3e018a2a> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Physical Analytes"@en .

rdfs:Resource rdfs:label "Resource" ;
    rdfs:comment "The class resource, everything." ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy rdfs: .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_fe982f99> skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> ;
    skos:note "This group contains RISE parameters classified under parameterGroupId 14: Gage Height. It also includes gage height parameters reported by usgs-sta, snotel-edr, and other sources.  Gage height (or stage) represents the height of the water surface relative to a reference level, known as a datum. When a datum is defined, measurements are referenced to a fixed elevation (e.g., mean sea level or a local benchmark), allowing for consistent comparison across time and locations. In contrast, values reported without a defined datum are relative measurements and may not be directly comparable across sites.  In cases where the datum is not defined, these measurements can be interpreted as water depth. For this reason, such parameters may also be considered within the River Characteristics group."@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "River Characteristics"@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_8257cf0e> .

<http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core> rdfs:seeAlso <http://www.w3.org/TR/skos-reference/> .

<http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_ee622e19> skos:broader <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#c_daa5e1ca> ;
    skos:inScheme <http://lincolninst.edu/cgs/vocabularies/usbr#conceptScheme_3e018a2a> ;
